      "type": "edit",
      "id": "6658a850-e334-4cdc-ba7a-2c189d52b1ab",
      "item": {
        "id": "6658a850-e334-4cdc-ba7a-2c189d52b1ab",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Melba studied singing in Melbourne and made a modest success in performances there. After a brief and unsuccessful marriage, she moved to Europe in search of a singing career. Failing to find engagements in London in 1886, she studied in Paris and soon made a great success there and in Brussels. Returning to London she quickly established herself as the leading lyric soprano at Covent Garden from 1888. She soon achieved further success in Paris and elsewhere in Europe, and later at the Metropolitan Opera in New York, debuting there in 1893. Her repertoire was small; in her whole career she sang no more than 25 roles and was closely identified with only ten. She was known for her performances in French and Italian opera, but sang little German opera."
      },
      "date": 1514562683956
